noun.description: An instance of casting more votes than is permissible at an election.

verb.description: To defeat by a majority of votes; = "outvote". Now rare.
And without object. To cast more than the permissible number of votes for a post, candidate, etc., or on a ballot paper, at an election.

origin: 1960s; earliest use found in The Washington Post. From over- + vote<br>mid 17th century; earliest use found in Cornelius Burges (d. 1665), Church of England clergyman and ejected minister. From over- + vote.
